		<div class="shareTools sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet" data-url="//www.nytimes.com/politics/first-draft/2015/04/09/today-in-politics-a-knighted-bloomberg-decrees-bush-and-clinton-worthy-candidates/" data-title="Today in Politics: A Knighted Bloomberg Decrees Bush and Clinton Worthy Candidates" data-description="Michael R. Bloomberg offers an opinion on the presidential race, and Gov. Chris Christie sees his approval ratings drop in New Jersey."></div>	</div>
	<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">  <div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/04/09/us/politics/09firstdraft-bloomberg/09firstdraft-bloomberg-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/04/09/us/politics/09firstdraft-bloomberg/09firstdraft-bloomberg-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/04/09/us/politics/09firstdraft-bloomberg/09firstdraft-bloomberg-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000003618490" width="592" height="395" alt="Michael R. Bloomberg, the former New York mayor, received an honorary knighthood on Wednesday in Washington, making him Knight Commander of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="395"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Michael R. Bloomberg, the former New York mayor, received an honorary knighthood on Wednesday in Washington, making him Knight Commander of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Thibault Camus/Associated Press</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Good Thursday morning from Washington, where <strong>President Obama</strong> has left town for Jamaica, and the White House has been having a bit of fun at <strong>Benjamin Netanyahu</strong>âs expense. <strong>Senator Rand Paul</strong> has been a little testy in his first day as a real presidential candidate, while <strong>Gov. Chris Christie</strong>âs charm offensive is falling flat in New Jersey. And a newly knighted <strong>Michael R. Bloomberg</strong>, who seems to be enjoying life after politics, tells us how he really feels about becoming Londonâs next mayor. </em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Michael R. Bloomberg</strong> beamed when <strong>Joanna Coles</strong>, the silver-haired British editor of Cosmopolitan, said she might like to borrow his lovely ânecklace.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But there was no way he was taking off the bling. The supreme Anglophile received a supreme honor from Queen Elizabeth II on Wednesday: an honorary knighthood.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">At a formal investiture ceremony at the British ambassadorâs residence in Washington, the ambassador, <strong>Peter Westmacott</strong>, presented the former New York mayor with the insignia marking him as a Knight Commander of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The queen smiled down from an <strong>Andy Warhol</strong> silk-screen.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And <strong>Vice President Joseph R. Biden Jr.,</strong> <strong>Colin Powell</strong>, <strong>Tina Brown</strong> and <strong>Harold Evans</strong> were on hand for the lunch of 2008 Meursault, cheese soufflÃ©, roasted flounder, and chocolate and mint parfait, as were Mr. Bloombergâs girlfriend, <strong>Diana Taylor</strong>; his British former wife, Susan; his daughters, Emma and Georgina, who are British citizens; and his baby grandson.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âBack in New York,&#8221; Mr. Bloomberg told the guests, âa good friend of mine â this is a friend of long standing â he said to me that this is only a honorary knighthood, and it doesnât make me either a knight or a commander, nor does it come with a title âsir,â and I said to him, âWell, thank you, <strong>Sir Paul McCartney</strong>.â &#8220;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But the 73-year-old billionaire was clearly delighted, calling the honor âas good as it gets.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âIâve always admired the sophistication and fortitude of the British people,&#8221; he said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Even though he is building two giant bronze-and-stone towers in London on the site of the ruins of a Roman temple to house his company and charity, and has become a patron of the arts there, he denied a report in The Sunday Times of London that he wants to run for mayor, succeeding <strong>Boris Johnson</strong>, whom he describes as âa kindred spirit.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âZero chance, zero interest,&#8221; he said flatly.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">When asked what he thought of the growing field of presidential candidates, Mr. Bloomberg was equally definite. âHillary and Jeb are the only two who know how to make the trains run,&#8221; he said, to get people back to work.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">With that, the knight of Gotham went back to showing off his new necklace.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>&#8212; Maureen Dowd</em></p>
<h4 id="post-mb-2" class="entry-title" style="font-size:16px; margin-top:20px; margin-bottom:20px;"><a class="nyt-dynamic-url" href="#post-mb-2" rel="bookmark"></a></h4>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong><em>Stay tuned throughout the day <a href="//p.nytimes.com/email/re?&#038;user_id=35471030bbf0d762449badb0500ad35e&#038;email_type=int-firstdraft-realtime&#038;task_id=1428468768819850&#038;regi_id=0" rel="nofollow">@NYTpolitics</a> for <a href="//p.nytimes.com/email/re?&#038;user_id=35471030bbf0d762449badb0500ad35e&#038;email_type=int-firstdraft-realtime&#038;task_id=1428468768819850&#038;regi_id=0" rel="nofollow">First Draft updates</a>.</em></strong></p>
<h4 id="post-mb-3" class="entry-title" style="font-size:16px; margin-top:20px; margin-bottom:20px;"><a class="nyt-dynamic-url" href="#post-mb-3" rel="bookmark">What Weâre Watching Today</a></h4>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> <strong>President Obama</strong> meets with <strong>Prime Minister Portia Simpson-Miller</strong> in Jamaica before heading to Panama.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> The <a href="//www.press.org/events/hillary-history-lessons-improve-open-government-under-records-laws-clintons-email-records-epi" rel="nofollow">National Press Club holds a 10 a.m. panel</a> on the policy implications surrounding <strong>Hillary Rodham Clinton</strong>âs use of a private email account as secretary of state.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> <strong>Senator Ted Cruz</strong> of Texas makes two stops in Des Moines.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> <strong>Christine Lagarde</strong>, managing director of the International Monetary Fund, <a href="//www.atlanticcouncil.org/events/webcasts/why-we-need-a-strong-imf-a-conversation-with-christine-lagarde" rel="nofollow">discusses the global economy at the Atlantic Council. </a></p>
<h4 id="post-mb-4" class="entry-title" style="font-size:16px; margin-top:20px; margin-bottom:20px;"><a class="nyt-dynamic-url" href="#post-mb-4" rel="bookmark">Rand Paul Raises Cash and Ruffles Feathers</a></h4>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Thinking about running for the Republican presidential nomination? Be ready to raise a million dollars in your first day as a candidate.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Senator Rand Paul</strong> of Kentucky was the latest to announce a White House bid, and he also became the latest million-dollar man, <a href="//randpaul.com/" rel="nofollow">surpassing a seven-digit donation tally</a> by Wednesday afternoon.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The total was in line with the $1 million that <strong>Senator Ted Cruz</strong> raised within 24 hours of his announcement last month.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Despite reaching that threshold, Mr. Paul had a combative first official day on the campaign trail, sparring with reporters over his views on foreign policy and abortion. On social media, he was widely described as âtesty.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Paul also sought to show his frugal side, posting a video of himself <a href="https://www.facebook.com/video.php?v=10152968008801107" rel="nofollow">dining at a McDonaldâs in New Hampshire</a> and declaring that his team was eating lunch off the dollar menu to make sure that donations were being spent wisely.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">While Mr. Paulâs opening day âmoney bombâ was successful enough, Mr. Cruz appears to have raised the bar higher. The Texas senatorâs political action committee backers have <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/04/09/us/super-pacs-network-quickly-raises-31-million-for-ted-cruz.html?hp&#038;action=click&#038;pgtype=Homepage&#038;module=first-column-region&#038;region=top-news&#038;WT.nav=top-news&#038;assetType=nyt_now" rel="nofollow">raised $31 million already</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">At the very least, the Cruz campaign will be well fed.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em> </em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>â Alan Rappeport</em></p>
<h4 id="post-mb-5" class="entry-title" style="font-size:16px; margin-top:20px; margin-bottom:20px;"><a class="nyt-dynamic-url" href="#post-mb-5" rel="bookmark">Bulletins: Poking Netanyahu, Masto Runs, Capps Retires</a></h4>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> <a href="//www.nytimes.com/politics/first-draft/2015/04/08/white-house-uses-twitter-to-take-a-poke-at-netanyahu/" rel="nofollow">Is the White House </a>trolling<strong> Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu</strong> of Israel to sell the nuclear framework deal with Iran? It certainly appeared that way on Wednesday, when the official White House Twitter account posted an image depicting a cartoon bomb with its fuse being snipped to illustrate how the accord would âshut down Iranâs pathway to a nuclear weapon.â<a href="https://www.twitter.com/WhiteHouse/status/585879181520728064/photo/1" rel="nofollow">The picture</a> (with the hashtag, naturally, #IranDeal) was reminiscent of a diagram Mr. Netanyahu presented at the United Nations General Assembly in September 2012 that showed a bomb with a fuse sticking out of the top and a blast at the end.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> The race to succeed <strong>Senator Harry Reid</strong> in Nevada <a href="//www.nytimes.com/politics/first-draft/2015/04/08/catherine-masto-ex-attorney-general-in-nevada-announces-bid-to-succeed-harry-reid/" rel="nofollow">has its first candidate.</a><strong>Catherine Cortez Masto</strong>, a Democrat and former attorney general in Nevada, <a href="//linkis.com/nvrdc.wordpress.com/aQ9Zg" rel="nofollow">announced Wednesday </a>that she was running for the seat of <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/03/28/us/politics/senator-harry-reid-retire.html" rel="nofollow">Mr. Reid</a>, who is retiring next year.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> <strong>Representative Lois Capps</strong>, a California Democrat who has represented the Santa Barbara area in Congress since succeeding her husband in 1998, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/politics/first-draft/2015/04/08/representative-lois-capps-announces-retirement/" rel="nofollow">announced Wednesday that she would not seek re-election next year</a>.</p>
<h4 id="post-mb-6" class="entry-title" style="font-size:16px; margin-top:20px; margin-bottom:20px;"><a class="nyt-dynamic-url" href="#post-mb-6" rel="bookmark">Charm Offensive Failing to Lift Christieâs Ratings at Home</a></h4>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Gov. Chris Christie</strong> of New Jersey has been hoping that rejuvenating his presidential bid will start at home, but a new poll suggests the climb will be steep. And the next weeks are likely to bring only more challenges, with the possibility of indictments in the <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/04/09/nyregion/indictments-may-be-near-in-george-washington-bridge-scandal.html" rel="nofollow">George Washington Bridge lane-closing scandal as early as next week.</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//eagletonpoll.rutgers.edu/rep-christie-ratings-apr2015" rel="nofollow">A Rutgers-Eagleton poll released Thursday</a> shows disapproval for the job Mr. Christie is doing at its highest level of his five-year tenure. Fifty-four percent of New Jersey registered voters disapprove of the overall job he is doing as governor, while 41 percent approve. New Jersey is a blue state, but he showed a marked drop even among his fellow Republicans, with job approval down 10 points, to 69 percent, and disapproval up 11 points, to 27 percent.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The results reinforce the slump Mr. Christie has seen in other polls, particularly as voters increasingly say he is more focused on running for president than on running New Jersey.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He also seems to have fallen from the national conversation about Republican contenders for 2016, damaged by the bridge controversy, doubts about his conservative credentials and New Jerseyâs bleak finances.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The governor has tried to revive his fortunes with a charm offensive recently, returning to the town-hall-style meetings that made him popular. He had planned to take his show on the road next week, with events in New Hampshire.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But the meetings in New Jersey have not done the trick. The Rutgers poll found Mr. Christie hitting new depths of displeasure on the state budget and on taxes. Disapproval of his handling of the economy and jobs held steady at 60 percent.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Notably, feelings about his handling of the Hurricane Sandy recovery â once a source of strength â are also diminished.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The poll, conducted March 27 to April 3 among 722 registered voters, has a margin of error of plus or minus four percentage points.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>&#8212; Kate Zernike</em></p>
<h4 id="post-mb-7" class="entry-title" style="font-size:16px; margin-top:20px; margin-bottom:20px;"><a class="nyt-dynamic-url" href="#post-mb-7" rel="bookmark">Our Favorites From Todayâs Times</a></h4>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> Mark Leibovich explains what it really means <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/04/12/magazine/what-it-really-means-to-call-hillary-clinton-polarizing.html?smid=fb-nytimes&#038;smtyp=cur&#038;bicmp=AD&#038;bicmlukp=WT.mc_id&#038;bicmst=1409232722000&#038;bicmet=1419773522000" rel="nofollow">to call <strong>Hillary Rodham Clinton</strong> âpolarizing.â</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> <strong><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/04/09/us/politics/obama-to-call-for-end-to-conversion-therapies-for-gay-and-transgender-youth.html?hp&#038;action=click&#038;pgtype=Homepage&#038;module=first-column-region&#038;region=top-news&#038;WT.nav=top-news" rel="nofollow">President Obama</a></strong> wants to ban âconversionâ therapies for gay and transgender youth.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> The director of the C.I.A. said that <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/04/09/world/middleeast/cia-director-says-irans-economic-peril-helped-drive-nuclear-deal.html?ref=politics" rel="nofollow">economic turmoil</a> pushed Iran to the negotiating table.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> Citizen videos are <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/04/09/us/video-of-fatal-shooting-of-walter-scott-reignites-debate-on-police-use-of-force.html?hp&#038;action=click&#038;pgtype=Homepage&#038;module=first-column-region&#038;region=top-news&#038;WT.nav=top-news" rel="nofollow">fueling a debate over police tactics</a> in the United States.</p>
<h4 id="post-mb-8" class="entry-title" style="font-size:16px; margin-top:20px; margin-bottom:20px;"><a class="nyt-dynamic-url" href="#post-mb-8" rel="bookmark">What Weâre Reading Elsewhere</a></h4>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> <strong>Hillary Rodham Clinton</strong> wrote a late-night message on Twitter <a href="https://www.twitter.com/HillaryClinton/status/586006768834215936" rel="nofollow">calling for an overhaul of the criminal justice system</a> after the death of Walter L. Scott.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> The Milwaukee Journal Sentinel argues that <strong>Gov. Scott Walker</strong>âs budget is not <a href="//www.jsonline.com/news/opinion/walkers-budget-taking-state-in-wrong-direction-on-runoff-pollution-b99476676z1-298936491.html" rel="nofollow">helping Wisconsinâs runoff pollution problem.</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> <strong>Martin Baron</strong>, editor of The Washington Post, <a href="//www.washingtonpost.com/pr/wp/2015/04/08/washington-post-executive-editor-martin-baron-on-journalisms-transition-from-print-to-digital/" rel="nofollow">gave a sweeping lecture</a> on the forces upending media.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> Politico tracks more <a href="//www.politico.com/story/2015/04/moroccan-cash-flows-to-clinton-foundation-116780.html" rel="nofollow">foreign donations</a> flowing into the Clinton Foundation.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> <strong>Chelsea Manning</strong> tells Cosmopolitan about <a href="//www.cosmopolitan.com/politics/a38728/chelsea-manning-may-2015/" rel="nofollow">her transition to living as a woman</a> in prison.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> <strong>Senator Ted Cruz</strong> of Texas tells John Harwood of CNBC <a href="//www.cnbc.com/id/102570532" rel="nofollow">how avocados make him sick</a> and how he enjoyed playing the villain in high school theater.</p>
